      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Skeptics argue that substantive due process is inherently vague and allows judges to impose their own personal policy preferences onto the law, which is judicial activism. They claim this allows unelected judges to substitute their views for the will of the democratically elected legislature. Furthermore, critics contend that relying on this doctrine creates an unpredictable legal landscape, undermining the stability of the rule of law.",
      "source": "target",
